*******************************************************************************
         README - P2P Simulator - WhatsTrust + URL Extension Edition
                     Original: A. West - JAVA Edition
               Extended by: Hatoon Almobadel, Lamya Alkathery, Gheed Alhoseine
                    King Saud University - CSC 489 
*******************************************************************************

INTRODUCTION:
This P2P simulator is used in the evaluation of trust management algorithms. It
consists of two major elements: (1) A 'trace generator' that outputs trace
files describing a network initialization and transactions, and (2) A
'simulator' that takes a trace and trust algorithm as input, simulates the
network run, and outputs statistics about how the trust manager performed.

This edition extends the original simulator with the WhatsTrust + URL
Classification algorithm (WhatsTrustTM), which adds a URL-based phishing
detection layer on top of the original WhatsTrust (Socialtrust) algorithm.
This directly addresses the future work stated in Almuzaini et al. (2020):
"Extend WhatsTrust to include message-based trust management systems."

*******************************************************************************
TRACE GENERATION:
*******************************************************************************
Traces are generated by running 'java TraceGenerator'. Customization of traces
is achieved at the command line. All arguments are optional, as the program
uses defaults for those not provided. The output should have a *.trace
extension. Otherwise, the below listing should be self-explanatory:

> -users:         (int) # of users/nodes/peers in network
> -files:         (int) # of distinct files in network
> -trans:         (int) # of transactions to simulate
> -zipf:          (float) Zipf constant controlling file popularity
> -output:        (string) Filename for trace output (*.trace)
>
> -usr:pre_trusted: (int) # of 'pre-trusted' users, a subset of 'good'
> -usr:purely:      (int) # of 'purely malicious' users
> -usr:feedback:    (int) # of 'feedback skewing' users
> -usr:provider:    (int) # of 'malicious provider' users
> -usr:disguise:    (int) # of 'disguised malicious' users
> -usr:sybil:       (int) # of 'Sybil attack' users
>
> -band:max_conn: (int) # of max upload/download connections per user
> -band:period:   (int) # of time units each upload/download requires
>
> -mode:smartgen: (bool) Use intelligent transaction generation?
> -mode:warmup:   (int) # of warm-up transactions before statistic tabulation

Note that only malicious user counts are specified at the command line. The
remainder of users will be initialized as type 'good.'

*******************************************************************************
TRUST SIMULATION:
*******************************************************************************
Simulations are performed by running 'java TraceSimulator'. The program takes
just three arguments; the input trace file, the trust management algorithm to
use, and a malicious strategy. All arguments are required:

> -input:     (string) Input trace file per 'TraceGenerator' creation (*.trace)
> -tm:        (string) Descriptor of trust management algorithm to simulate
> -strategy:  (string) Descriptor of malicious strategy to simulate

The argument provided to '-tm' must be an algorithm already implemented
within the system. Currently, the following algorithms are implemented:

> 'eigen':      The EigenTrust algorithm of Hector Garcia-Molina, et al.
> 'etinc':      Similar to EigenTrust, but experimenting with speedup strategies.
> 'tnasl':      System using Subjective Logic operators, inspired by Josang et al.
> 'none':       Absence of trust management. Essentially random source selection.
> 'whatstrust': WhatsTrust + URL Classification (NEW - see section below).

Similarly, the possible arguments to '-strategy' are pre-programmed:

> 'naive':      Global interaction data is used exclusively
> 'isolated':   Local honest interaction history overwrites global one
> 'collective': All malicious peers share honest information with each other

Running the simulator will create an output file. The file will contain
statistics about the simulation. The extension of the output file will equal
that of the trust-management-algorithm employed. For example, if 'trace_0.trace'
is simulated using 'whatstrust', the output file will be 'trace_0.whatstrust'.

*******************************************************************************
WHATSTRUST + URL CLASSIFICATION (NEW ALGORITHM):
*******************************************************************************
The WhatsTrust + URL algorithm extends the original WhatsTrust (Socialtrust)
with a two-gate trust decision system:

  Gate 1 - User Trust  : WhatsTrust Subjective Logic (sender trust >= 0.5)
  Gate 2 - URL Trust   : ML-based URL phishing classification (URLTrust)

Both gates must PASS for a message to be accepted:

  User trusted + URL safe     -> ACCEPTED
  User trusted + URL phishing -> REJECTED  <- KEY CONTRIBUTION
  User not trusted + any URL  -> REJECTED

The key contribution is the second row: even when a sender is fully trusted
by WhatsTrust, if their message contains a phishing URL, it is rejected.
This simulates the real-world scenario where good users unknowingly forward
phishing URLs — a threat the original WhatsTrust cannot detect.

When phishing is detected, a fake bad transaction is injected into WhatsTrust's
Subjective Logic mechanism, naturally lowering the sender's trust score for
future transactions without using arbitrary penalty values.

NEW FILES (place in src/ folder):
  trust_system_lib/WhatsTrustTM.java  - The extended algorithm
  trust_system_lib/URLTrust.java      - Independent URL trust layer
  classify_urls_batch.py              - Batch URL classifier (Python)
  prepare_messages.py                 - Message file generator (Python)
  url_classifier_final.py             - ML model trainer (Python)
  parse_results.py                    - Results parser and chart generator
  run_all.bat                         - Batch runner for all experiments

REQUIRED BEFORE RUNNING:
Before running WhatsTrust simulations, execute these steps once:

  Step 1: python url_classifier_final.py
          (trains Random Forest model, saves test URLs)

  Step 2: python prepare_messages.py
          (creates good_messages.txt, bad_messages.txt, forwarded_msgs.txt)

  Step 3: javac -cp "." trust_system_lib\URLTrust.java
          javac -cp "." trust_system_lib\WhatsTrustTM.java

PATHS TO UPDATE:
Open WhatsTrustTM.java and update the 7 path constants at the top of the file
to match your machine (replace 'Hatna' with your Windows username):

  PYTHON_PATH    - path to your Python executable
  BATCH_SCRIPT   - path to classify_urls_batch.py
  GOOD_MSG_PATH  - path to good_messages.txt
  BAD_MSG_PATH   - path to bad_messages.txt
  FWD_MSG_PATH   - path to forwarded_msgs.txt
  URL_INPUT_FILE - path to urls_to_classify.txt (temp file)
  URL_OUTPUT_FILE- path to url_results.txt (temp file)

RUNNING ALL EXPERIMENTS:
  .\run_all.bat
  python parse_results.py

EXAMPLE SINGLE RUN:
  java -cp "." TraceSimulator -input trace_10101.trace -tm whatstrust -strategy naive

OUTPUT FILE FORMAT:
The .whatstrust output file follows the same format as .eigen files and contains:
  - Trace parameters
  - Transaction overview
  - Good user success rate (primary evaluation metric)
  - URL detection statistics

*******************************************************************************
DATASETS REQUIRED:
*******************************************************************************
  1. SMS Spam Collection (spam.csv)
     Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository
     Used for: Real message text (ham/spam)

  2. PhiUSIIL Phishing URL Dataset (PhiUSIIL_Phishing_URL_Dataset.csv)
     Source: UCI Machine Learning Repository
     Used for: Training ML model + source of simulation URLs

Note: The three message files (good_messages.txt, bad_messages.txt,
forwarded_msgs.txt) are pre-generated and included. You only need the
datasets if you want to regenerate the message files.

